explanation:
For determining whether any operations in OS_FileSysMountVolume_Impl are dead code, the analyzer must know exactly which expressions/operations produce observable effects and which values/conditions govern control flow. Each symbol below is required for that analysis:

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: macro/lookup used to obtain the local record; needed to know whether it can have side effects or compute different records (affects reachability and behavior).
- OS_filesys_table: backing table used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; needed to know semantics of the lookup and whether local can be NULL/invalid.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: appears in call graph as the token->index mechanism; needed to understand lookup semantics and any side effects of obtaining the object.
- OS_filesys_internal_record_t: definition of the record type returned by the lookup; required to know what fields exist and their semantics.
- OS_object_token_t: token type used to index the table; needed to reason about how the token value affects which record is selected (control-flow / observable effect differences).
- system_mountpt (field): string pathname used in stat/mkdir/DEBUG; required because operations on this path (mkdir/stat) are observable external effects (filesystem changes) and determine whether code is dead.
- fstype (field): governs final if-statement that may return NOT_IMPLEMENTED; needed to determine which branch executes and whether the check is meaningful.
- struct stat: layout/type required to interpret stat results and st_mode for S_ISDIR; needed to assess whether the S_ISDIR test can be evaluated and its side effects.
- stat (function): invoked to test existence/type of mount point — this call is an observable filesystem access; needed to decide if the call (or its removal) changes program behaviour.
- S_ISDIR (macro): interprets st_mode to determine directory status; required to decide whether the else-if branch can produce the DEBUG+return path.
- mkdir (function): creates the directory; a clear external side effect — must be considered when determining whether code removal changes behavior.
- errno (variable): used by strerror and to diagnose error from mkdir/stat; needed to interpret error reporting behavior (observable via logging) and whether errors cause returns.
- strerror (function): used inside OS_DEBUG to produce human-readable error text; affects output side-effects (logging) that may matter for observable behaviour.
- OS_DEBUG: logging function/macro called on error paths; logging is an observable effect — required to decide if removing the code would change externally visible behavior.
- OS_FS_ERR_DRIVE_NOT_CREATED: return value used on mount-point creation/type failure; required because return codes are part of observable behavior (API contract).
- OS_FILESYS_TYPE_VOLATILE_DISK: filesystem-type constant used in the fstype check; needed to determine which branch is taken.
- OS_FILESYS_TYPE_FS_BASED: other filesystem-type constant used in fstype check; needed similarly.
- OS_ERR_NOT_IMPLEMENTED: return value used when mount is not implemented for the FS type; required to decide whether removing the check/return would affect externally-visible return codes.
- OS_SUCCESS: final return value when nothing fails; required to reason about observable return behavior when code is retained vs removed.

In short: to decide whether any operation in the function is dead code (i.e., its removal would not change program behaviour), the analyzer needs the lookup semantics (how local is selected), the filesystem calls and their side effects (stat, mkdir), the error/logging interactions (errno, strerror, OS_DEBUG), and the constants/fields that determine control flow and return values (fstype and the OS_* constants). Without these symbols the agent cannot determine whether a branch or call produces observable effects and thus whether it is dead code.
